A formalisable hypothesis is one that can be restated as a precise, testable mathematical or logical statement, typically of the form: "Under assumptions A1...An, quantity X stands in relation R to quantity Y." To extract one from a paper's prose claim, first identify the core assertion stripped of hedging, motivation, and rhetorical framing. Next, isolate the population or domain over which the claim ranges, since prose often leaves the quantifier implicit (all, most, on average, in the limit). Then identify the dependent variable or outcome and the independent variable, treatment, or condition being related to it. Specify the direction and functional form of the claimed relationship: is it equality, inequality, monotonicity, proportionality, convergence, or a bound? Make the comparison class explicit, because prose claims like "method X is better" presuppose a baseline, a metric, and a regime. Surface any conditioning variables, scope restrictions, or ceteris paribus clauses that the authors assume but do not state. Convert vague quantitative language ("substantially", "approximately", "scales with") into parameters or thresholds that could in principle be measured. Distinguish existence claims ("there exists a setting where...") from universal claims ("for all settings..."), since these have very different formal content. Note whether the claim is asymptotic, finite-sample, worst-case, average-case, or high-probability, as these correspond to different formal templates. Identify the underlying probability space, data-generating process, or model class if the claim is statistical. Render the hypothesis in a canonical schema such as H: for all x in D satisfying C(x), f(x) R g(x) + epsilon, with all symbols defined. Separate the main hypothesis from auxiliary lemmas or empirical predictions that would corroborate it. Flag terms that resist formalisation (e.g. "understanding", "natural", "robust") and either operationalise them via a proxy or mark them as definitional debts. State the null or alternative against which the hypothesis would be tested, since a formalisable hypothesis must be falsifiable. Record the evidence type the authors offer (proof, simulation, benchmark, case study) because this constrains the formal frame. Finally, write the hypothesis in one sentence using bound variables, explicit quantifiers, and named constants, then list its assumptions as a numbered preamble. For example, the prose claim "larger language models generalise better" might formalise as: "For a fixed pretraining distribution P and evaluation benchmark B, expected zero-shot accuracy A(M) on B is a monotonically non-decreasing function of parameter count N(M) across a model family F trained with protocol T, for N in [N_min, N_max]." This makes the population (family F), the conditioning (P, B, T), the variable (N), the outcome (A), the relation (monotone non-decreasing), and the scope (bounded N range) all explicit and checkable.
